{{-- Apple Weather attribution (Story 11.3 / CAP-8). WeatherKit's license REQUIRES
     the Apple Weather mark + a link to Apple's legal data-source page wherever its
     data is shown — so this is gated on the active provider flag, never a feature
     toggle: the attribution can never be on with the data absent (or vice-versa).

     The mark is INLINED as a data URI (email clients strip remote images, and a
     hotlinked weatherkit.apple.com logo would silently vanish in many inboxes).
     The digest renders in dark mode too (its card goes #FFFFFF → #16232F), so both
     Apple marks ship: the black "blk" mark on the light card, the white "wht" mark
     swapped in under prefers-color-scheme:dark via the .tc-aw-* classes defined in
     the digest head. Apple's mark/wordmark is unaltered (trademark). --}}
@if (config('tripcast.forecast.provider') === 'weatherkit')
    <p class="tc-ink-secondary" style="margin:16px 0 0; font-family:-apple-system,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif; font-size:13px; line-height:20px; color:#51616E;">
        <a href="https://developer.apple.com/weatherkit/data-source-attribution/" class="tc-ink-secondary" style="color:#51616E; text-decoration:none;">
            <img class="tc-aw-light" alt="Apple Weather" width="77" height="14" src="data:image/png;base64," style="display:inline-block; width:77px; height:14px; border:0; vertical-align:middle;">
            <img class="tc-aw-dark" alt="Apple Weather" width="77" height="14" src="data:image/png;base64," style="display:none; width:77px; height:14px; border:0; vertical-align:middle; mso-hide:all;">
        </a>
    </p>
@endif
